ruitment Process',3,'<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">College is an incredible time of life full of new beginnings, self-discovery, and hardwork. For many students, this is the ideal start to the adult world. For college athletes, it&rsquo;s a different world full of many steps, contracts, and more.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Athletes understand the search for a college less as a transitioning moment and more as &ldquo;The College Recruitment Process.&rdquo; Vixory understands this lofty undertaking, and we&rsquo;re here to help! In today&rsquo;s blog, we&rsquo;ll discuss the college recruitment process and things to consider while completing it.</span></span></span></p>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">When Should I Know To Look For Recruiters At My Games?</span></span></span></h2>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">According to the</span></span></span><a href=\"https://www.ncaa.org/student-athletes/future/recruiting\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u> NCAA</u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">, recruiters stick to a strict rotating calendar based on the </span></span></span><a href=\"https://www.ncaa.org/student-athletes/resources/recruiting-calendars/division-i-and-ii-recruiting-calendars\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u>sport currently being featured</u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">. Specific calendars are offered on their site, but the general understanding is that coaches and recruiters will cycle through the sport of their interest during the season. Fall sports will see recruiters during the fall, etc.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">How Do I Know I&rsquo;m Being Recruited?</span></span></span></h2>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">The recruiting process can sometimes be a bit confusing. Vixory understands this, which is why below we&rsquo;ve covered an outline of the process to keep you informed as you move forward.</span></span></span></p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li style=\"list-style-type:disc\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">You will be told</span></span></span>\n\n	<ul>\n		<li style=\"list-style-type:circle\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">According to the NCAA rules, anytime a college coach speaks to you about sports&mdash;other than a hello&mdash; it&rsquo;s considered a <strong>contact. </strong>Coaches making contact with players signal their interest in starting the recruiting process.&nbsp;</span></span></span></li>\n	</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li style=\"list-style-type:disc\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">You will be evaluated</span></span></span>\n	<ul>\n		<li style=\"list-style-type:circle\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Coaches attending your games are evaluating how you play and how your style will fit their team. When a coach is watching your game, know that it is an evaluation that could lead to more, so play your best!</span></span></span></li>\n	</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li style=\"list-style-type:disc\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">You will be invited for an official visit (DI and D2)</span></span></span>\n	<ul>\n		<li style=\"list-style-type:circle\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Official visits are college visits paid for by the university. These visits include roundtrip travel expenses, three meals a day while on-site, and tickets for you and your family for up to three sporting events. Being invited for an official visit occurs after a successful player evaluation. If a coach is impressed by your evaluation, they will likely invite you for an official visit.&nbsp;</span></span></span></li>\n	</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li style=\"list-style-type:disc\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">You will receive an official offer and be asked for a verbal commitment&nbsp;</span></span></span>\n	<ul>\n		<li style=\"list-style-type:circle\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">A verbal commitment is when a player verbally agrees to attend a university for athletics. These commitments are non-binding but often lead to signings, as they signal to the coach the player is serious about their interest. If you are presented with the opportunity to give a verbal, it is likely you will have the opportunity to follow up and sign your letter of intent.</span></span></span></li>\n	</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li style=\"list-style-type:disc\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">You will sign a letter of intent</span></span></span>\n	<ul>\n		<li style=\"list-style-type:circle\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Letters of intent are issued through the NCAA, and are the official binding contract that solidifies a player&rsquo;s spot on the team and in the school for the next year. If you are presented one, chances are you know that you are attending college and playing athletics at the school you are signing for.&nbsp;</span></span></span></li>\n	</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Which Schools Are Required To Officially Recruit Through The NCAA?</span></span></span></h2>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Believe it or not, not all schools follow the same recruiting process. Division I and Division II athletics must follow a similar path due to the prestigious nature of the institutions. Signings of intent are an example. DI and DII schools must present a player with an intent form in order to contract them to the team. DIII schools, on the other hand, are allowed to present a celebratory signing form as more of a symbolic measure.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\n\n<h2><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:17pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Register For Vixory Today!</span></span></span></h2>\n\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Recruiting season begins soon, and at Vixory we work to make sure all student-athletes feel prepared. We do our best to assist in everything from connecting you to your future coach to offering tips on the transfer process. If you&rsquo;re a transferring student-athlete, or simply want to keep up with the community, sign up with us today! We&rsquo;re looking forward to connecting with you!</span></span>&nbsp;</span></p>','2022-01-19 18:08:29','2022-01-19 18:13:45','Vixory Provides Insight On The College Recruitment Process','In todays blog, Vixory will cover the college recruitment process and some tips to consider.',0,'Z5HZFINW7zkzYpKEO5aYqu979F1zFk28GUCHdy0D.jpg','In todays blog, Vixory will cover the college recruitment process and some tips to consider.'),(15,'What Are Myths Associated With College Transfers? Vixory Debunks Them All',2,'<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">As college students grow and change, they learn their preferences, likes, wants, needs, dislikes, and more. Accordingly, they might change career paths, decide they don&rsquo;t like their current geographic area, or realize their first school is the wrong fit for their learning style. If so, they might want to transfer schools, which is a normal part of college culture. Vixory understands this, and today we want to debunk some typical myths surrounding college transfers.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Transferring Is Hard</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Transferring can be a detailed process, but it isn&rsquo;t meant to be a hard one. Knowing who to talk to, where to go to get your registration records, where to order and send your transcripts to, and when to sign up for classes at your new school can seem extremely overwhelming. It shouldn&rsquo;t be though. Today, there are many resources available to students completing the transfer process.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">There are even departments now for transfer and non-traditional students that help handle the process. If you&rsquo;re unsure of where to go to find this department, the counseling center, resource office, or registrar are great places to start. All of them are linked to the transfer center and will help connect you with your next resource.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Transferring Isn&rsquo;t Normal</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Young minds are used to living within a pack or group mindset. This is especially true for young athletes playing team sports. This is why it can be terrifying to consider the idea of transferring. But trust us, it&#39;s perfectly normal to transfer schools. According to the </span></span></span><a href=\"https://nscresearchcenter.org/tracking-transfer/\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u>National Student Clearing House</u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">, between 15-40% of students were college transfers.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">If you are interested in transferring to another institution, take your shot. You are among an entire population of students who have done the same. Many students transfer from community colleges to universities to save on cost. Joining the bracket and going for the transfer is normal, and will only enrich your life experience.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">My Credits Won&rsquo;t Transfer</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Not all credits will, but more might than you think. Oftentimes, private universities will offer a more flexible transfer than state universities due to having the freedom to craft their own curriculums. They are better able to judge the level of class than state schools are allowed to due to accreditation purposes.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">My Graduation Date Will Change</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">This is a hard one to combat, because a lot of different factors come into play. Most private universities offer a different curriculum than state universities, and there are regional variances to consider as well. However, if you incorporate strategic planning and hardwork into your already thriving athletic work ethic, you will graduate on time.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:17pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Vixory Supports All College Transfers</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Vixory understands times of transition are critical and must be handled with care. We do our best to assist in everything from connecting you to your future coach to offering tips on the transfer process. If you&rsquo;re a transferring student-athlete, or simply want to keep up with the community, sign up with us today! We&rsquo;re looking forward to connecting with you!</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2022-01-31 02:26:50','2022-01-31 02:29:43','Vixory Debunks College Transfer Myths','In todays blog, Vixory will cover myths involved with college transfers and reveal the truth.',0,'bPsvG6UWn59MB0UUQQAhDQQDIO6bxkCr3isykiiH.jpg','In todays blog, Vixory will cover myths involved with college transfers and reveal the truth.'),(16,'Transfer Differences in DI versus DII, Vixory Weighs In',2,'<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">For collegiate student-athletes, the thought of transferring to a different school is common. Sometimes the experience at their first college sports program is not what they had hoped for, which prompts the athlete to consider making a switch. The transfer process can look a bit different depending on if the athlete is in a DI or DII program. In today&rsquo;s blog, </span></span></span><a href=\"https://vixory.com/\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u>Vixory</u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"> will help you understand the differences between transferring to a DI school versus a DII school.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">DI versus DII: Are Transfer Rules Different?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">The simple answer is: it depends. NCAA transfer rules and regulations that apply to the student-athlete will depend on the division and conference of the school they are looking to transfer to. The process will look different for athletes looking to uplevel and move from DII to DI compared to those seeking a transition to a new DI school. As well, the conference that you are looking to join at your new school may have its own unique transfer rules and regulations, followed by the process of being admitted to the school. As these differences are dependent on the school and conference, in general, the beginning of the process for DI transfers and DII transfers are fairly similar.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">The NCAA provides a </span></span></span><a href=\"http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/eligibility_center/Transfer/FourYearGuide.pdf\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u>printable guide</u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"> for athletes interested in transferring into a four-year university.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">How to Start the Transfer Process</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.ncaa.org/sports/2015/2/13/want-to-transfer.aspx\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u>NCAA officials recommend</u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"> that athletes who are seeking a transfer should first decide on the schools they are most interested in attending. Once this is decided, the athlete can then begin the process by requesting a notification of transfer from their compliance office at their current school, enter the transfer portal, and begin the admissions process. The administration side of this process may look different depending on which division the athlete is transferring into, but taking these specific steps is the best place for anyone to start!&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:17pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">What to Expect After a Transfer</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">In April of 2021, the NCAA voted to </span></span></span><a href=\"https://www.ncaa.org/news/2021/4/15/di-council-adopts-new-transfer-legislation.aspx\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u>change its transfer legislation</u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"> and allow all Divison I student-athletes a single opportunity to transfer to a different university and compete immediately, without having to sit out one season. This was great news for DI transfers all over the country, who no longer have to sit out of their particular sport for a period of time before hitting the field, track, court, or ice once again. Once the transfer is complete and the student-athlete is settled into their new campus and team, they can finally focus on what they do best.&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:17pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">Interested in a Transfer? Let Vixory Help!</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\">If you still have questions or concerns regarding the DI and DII transfer process, let the professionals at Vixory help you! Our mission is to help athletes find a school that fits their needs and talent, by providing an online platform that makes your transfer simple. </span></span></span><a href=\"https://vixory.com/\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u>Contact us today</u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"> to build your athletic career exactly where you want to be!</span></span></span></p>','2022-02-14 17:24:57','2022-02-14 17:24:57','DI versus DII: Are There Transfer Differences? Vixory Explains.','In todays blog, Vixory will cover the differences between transferring to a DI school versus a DII school.',0,'reuJBE0CkkVBgCz42FSkTkmAJSquzqtQfqwg73XZ.jpg','In todays blog, Vixory will cover the differences between transferring to a DI school versus a DII school.'),(18,'Financial Assistance Resources For Transferring Student-Athletes',3,'<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:#000000\">Financial assistance is significant for student-athlete college transfers and their success. Before enrolling in an institution, many students have access to financial aid resources like FAFSA, consisting of grants, scholarships, and student loans. Many forms of financial aid are available for college athletes, even if you are transferring to a different school. In today&rsquo;s blog, </span></span></span></span><a href=\"https://vixory.com/about\" style=\"text-decoration:none\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><u><span style=\"background-color:#000000\">Vixory</span></u></span></span></span></a><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:#000000\"> discusses financial assistance for collegiate student-athletes who are looking to transfer.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:17pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:#000000\">Types of Financial Aid Assistance For Student-Athletes:</span></span></span></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:#000000\">If you are a student-athlete enrolled in a university, looking into federal aid is the first step. FAFSA (Federal Application For Federal Student Aid) is an online form to determine your eligibility for college funding.&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:#000000\">All U.S. colleges work with FAFSA and fund based on student needs. Different institutions require this information for grants and scholarships as a first-year student or college transfer. Get in touch with the admissions office for your college of interest to learn more about FAFSA eligibility.&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:#000000\">Different types of financial aid for college transfers include:</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"list-style-type:decimal\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:#000000\">Merit Scholarships</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"list-style-type:decimal\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-color:#000000\">Pell Grants</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"list-style-type:decimal\"><span style=\"color:#ffffff\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Montserrat,sans-serif\"><span style=\"background-